# Frontend UI verification (Playwright)

Use this rule in every session, but enforce Playwright verification only when the task is frontend/UI-related.

Treat a task as frontend/UI-related when either is true:
- The user asks for UI, styling, layout, interactions, browser behavior, pages, components, or UX checks.
- Planned or actual changes touch frontend files (for example `apps/web/**`, `packages/ui/**`, `*.tsx`, `*.jsx`, `*.css`, `*.scss`, locale files, or client-side hooks).

If frontend/UI-related, verify the result in a real browser before declaring completion.

## Prerequisite

Read and follow `~/.codex/skills/playwright/SKILL.md`.
Use the Playwright CLI browser flow for verification unless the user explicitly asks for a different approach.

## Verification workflow

1. Start or reuse the required local app servers.
2. Open the affected route in a browser via Playwright CLI.
3. Exercise the changed UI flow (clicks, typing, forms, tabs, dialogs, navigation, error/empty states as applicable).
4. Re-snapshot after significant DOM changes to avoid stale refs.
5. Capture at least one screenshot when the change is visual or layout-related.

## What to confirm

- Changed UI renders correctly and matches user intent.
- Primary interactions in the touched area work end-to-end.
- No obvious regressions are introduced in the same view.

## Report back

When verification applies, include:
- route(s) opened,
- key actions performed,
- verification result (pass/fail),
- and blocker details if verification could not be completed.

## Exceptions

Skip browser verification only when the change cannot affect runtime UI at all (for example comments, server-only logic, or pure type edits). If uncertain, run Playwright verification.
